# String Trimming Convention

All string inputs must be trimmed **before** validation or persistence. Never rely on the caller to trim.

## In Zod Schemas

Use `.trim()` directly in the schema so trimming and validation happen atomically.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — trimming done manually at the call site, easy to forget
const schema = z.object({ name: z.string().min(1) });
const parsed = schema.parse({ name: input.name.trim() });

// ✅ GOOD — schema owns the trimming contract
const schema = z.object({ name: z.string().trim().min(1, "Name is required.") });
const parsed = schema.parse({ name: input.name });
```

Chain order matters: `.trim()` must come **before** `.min()` so min-length validation
runs on the trimmed value and whitespace-only strings are correctly rejected.

## In Prisma Middleware / Client Extensions

The project's `lib/prisma.ts` already runs a recursive `trimStrings()` on all
`create`, `update`, and `upsert` payloads. Do **not** duplicate trimming logic in
Server Actions for fields that go through Prisma — rely on the extension.

For fields that do **not** go through Prisma (e.g., search query params, URL
segments, email lookups), trim explicitly:

```typescript
// ✅ Trim before a Prisma lookup
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { email: rawEmail.trim().toLowerCase() },
});
```

## Quick Reference

| Location | Method |
|---|---|
| Zod schema fields | `.trim().min(1, "…")` |
| Non-Prisma string params | `value.trim()` at point of use |
| Prisma write payloads | Handled by `lib/prisma.ts` extension — no action needed |
